The Chronicle Innocent Kurira, Sports Reporter
THE Zimbabwe Tertiary Sports Union (ZTISU) games got underway in Bulawayo yesterday under the theme “Together we can achieve the extraordinary through sport”. The games are being hosted by Hillside Teachers College and were officially opened by Sports and Recreation Commission (SRC) regional deputy director Isaiah Mpofu at White City Stadium yesterday. <img class="wp-image-627502 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-32-9.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-32-9.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-32-9-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Isaiah Mpofu Mpofu said when properly managed, sport can be a unifier and challenged participants to show respect for competition rules. “These games are all about building a better society and this can only be achieved if we continue to interact through sports. “l urge all athletes to be at the forefront of this noble effort of unifying our beloved Zimbabwean society and eradicating gender imbalances,” said Mpofu. The games are being sponsored by Delta Beverages through its Carling Black Label brand to the tune of US$40 000. <img class="wp-image-626653 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-4-2.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-4-2.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-4-2-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Bulawayo Athletic Club Delta Beverages Belmont Plant acting manager Mthulisi Nyoni pledged continued support for the games in future. “We have been sponsoring the games for the past three years and we are proudly sponsoring these games this year as we continue to reward the champions at play. Sports play a pivotal role in building communities and resonate well with the brand’s manifesto.  “Carling Black Label will not only reward the achievers, but also reward efforts of the teams by sponsoring kits for two finalists in football, rugby, netball, volleyball and basketball,” said Nyoni. Edward Chekure, the ZTISU president, urged athletes to exercise fair play. “I want to congratulate all our athletes for making it up to this national event. Let’s all adhere to our code of conduct, which observes attributes of Ubuntu,” said Chekure. <img class="wp-image-627505 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-33-9.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-33-9.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-33-9-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Mthulisi Nyoni “From these games, only gold medalists will proceed to the CUCSA games from August 28 to September 3 in Malawi.” White City Stadium will host athletics and volleyball, while basketball will be held at Khanyisile Sports Centre, with handball and netball being staged at the United College of Education. Football is scheduled for the Barbourfields Stadium B Arena and Bulawayo Athletic Club is the tennis venue, while chess, darts and table tennis will be held at Hillside Teachers College. — @innocentskizoe